Statistical Summary¶

Here we can see that Experience column has min value as negative which is not possible because number of experience should be greater than or equal to zero.

Moreover, we have some categorical variables so for them the stats is not that meaningful. However, there are numeric columns such as Experience, Income, Family, CCAvg, Mortgage, CD account so we can get some idea with the below 5 points summary.

# Calculating Experience mean excluding negative values, so that it can be used for imputation. 
experience_mean = df[df['Experience']>=0]['Experience'].mean()
df.loc[df['Experience']<0,'Experience']=experience_mean

df['Experience'] = df['Experience'].round(2)

Conclusions¶

Business understanding of the model¶

Since the data was normalized and standardized before creating a model. We can look at the coefficient values and see what features are contributing the most towards Personal Loan being being opted by customers. Below are the coefficients values which was taken during the above analysis and modelling process.

Age = 0.540489, Experience = 0.500024, Income = 2.51459 , Family = 0.691058, CCAvg = 0.351407, Mortgage = 0.099219, Securities Account = -0.326485, CD Account = 0.852242, Online = -0.293757, CreditCard = -0.438716, Education_Advanced/Professional = 0.6469, Education_Graduate = 0.582551, Education_Undergrad = -1.131348

Here, the top 3 features with highest absolute coefficient values are Income, undergraduate qualification and account. Now looking at the actual signs of these 3 coefficients the income and CD Account variables are positive whereas undergraduate qualification variable is negative. So, from this perspective the bank should put more emphasis on customers with high income or have a cash deposit account. Customers having an ungraduate level of qualification has a negative high value which means the bank should put least amount of resources on such customers during their marketing campaign.

Our prediction model predicts 8.12% of the test sample would buy the 'Personal Loan' package from the bank. This is lower than the observed 9% of the customers opting for the Personal loan. The bank now has to decide whether to invest in the campaign or not and how much money should they invest in the campaign. Moreover, customer can use the predictive model, which has an accuracy of 0.95 and F1 score of 0.77 to predict if the customer is a potential buyer or not. Based on such predictions that bank can optimize its marketing campaign. Since the bank here do not want to lose potential customers, the sensitivity of the model is the parameter to look at from the confusion matrix. Our model has a sensitivity of 0.69 which means there might be some false positives. We have adjusted our threshold to get the highest possible True Positive Rate while retaining false positive rate to be minimum.

How can the model perform better?¶

The model can be improved by adjusting the threshold as we saw in the analysis performed above. Moreover, there are certain solver algorithms to chose from could give better performance[1]. Solvers provided by the sklearn's LogisticRegression are newton-cg, lbfgs, liblinear, sag and saga. The default solver here is lbfgs. [1]
